Just change textures only. AOID should be left alone at all times.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Which experience did you base this on ?
<br />
It's a wrong assumption. 
<br />

<br />
If you swap AOID you will end up with an unuseable item in your inventory. It happens sometimes without altering any file just cause of a bug. The server is always right and will use the real item you have. The client does not care. Your client has got a copy of the items that are "living" on the server side. Our client just represent an image, an essence of what is such an item. If you modify it client side, it's your problem. You will never have the benefice of your modification in the right direction. 
<br />

<br />
And yes, altering the DB ought to be used for texture swapping only. Adding texture is a huge huge modification including ctree compliance and a rebuild of the index. It can create big trouble in case of futur patching. 
<br />

<br />
But swapping textures by swapping int32 pointers (aoid) does not prevent patching. The DB is always patched even if you altered the file. Not like the .ldb file by example, that is never patched if you touched it before.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
