			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Kir, i base it from my experiences of reversing the AO client and making an offline server. We can add and delete items as we choose at the moment.
<br />

<br />
So obviously its you who needs to learn about packets in this regard.
<br />

<br />
0x11, 0x00, 0x01, 0x00, 0x01, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00,
<br />
0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, AOID, AOID,
<br />
AOID, 0x00, AOID, AOID, AOID, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00,
<br />
 0x01, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00,
<br />

<br />
Im not going to go into to much detail about the segment of this packet kir
<br />
as im not turnining this into a debate, But lets take a breif look. From what we can see the server for the neck slot (0x11) the AOID is what the server tells the client to equip. It bases this off the LOCAL database. If its hexed right and not corrupted the item will indeed be shown. Now of course the server has its own item hash tables. But the client STILL registers the stats. So whatever that AO ID is be it a nano or whatever it will put that item in the slot its told to.
<br />

<br />
With forged items the client still assumes the bonuses or whatever are in place, although the server does not. What this means is the client will sends updates like fake bonuses to equip an item and the server will reject what it percives as forged figures. This may alert GM to what your doing.
<br />

<br />
If you hex an AOID and get a no item error it simply means your AOID is borked. AOE at the moment allows users to add any aoid they like in their character file and if its an invalid number it will show as no item.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So Kir the server only sends the client a reference to the DB... not what it is, the client draws and modifies its internal values based opn the AOID in the local database.  I have put HNT on my foot because the server told the client to. However for the client to check if you can equip something (and yes the client does check first) it uses its local values FIRST. When they are forged and the client thinks its ok.. the server will get random numbers and as I said perhaps set off an alarm bell or two.
<br />

<br />
If by some means Kir your knowledge is bettere than practical proven results please let me know. If you have issues you can always download the latest sandbox to see my point. Try do somethign random like equip the rocketpack on your foot.  Its blatantly obvious the server checks things, but its a little naive to think the client has abolutley no local data input or error checking. (it doesnt send a check to the server when you try to use something you cant it kills the request clientside before constructing a packet, only if the client is exploited does the server get a chance to reject it) That is why changing MESHES is much safer.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
